We discovered the enchanting, “hidden” passages of Paris today, biking from one to another to another… These beautiful “passages” were built in the 1800’s when the streets of Paris were primitive and any rain or snow would render them muddy and impossible to navigate.
The passages were the “shopping malls” of the day, intricately built with exquisite domed glass/metal ceilings, gorgeous tile floors, carved wood and stone interiors - 150 of them in all! Sadly, when Paris was “modernized” in the 1900’s, many of the beautiful passages were taken down. There are 20 left today and they are quite spectacular, each one having a personality of its own and housing restaurants, boutiques, bars, cafes, grocery stores, hotels… you name it!
A fun, fascinating day but we are TIRED after 20 miles on the bikes! Night, night! #cafesucrefarine #ontheroadagain #iloveparis #ilovefrance #cafesucreadventures

You’ve heard of “the butcher, the baker and the candlestick maker”, right? That’s who we went to see this morning. 

We decided to pack a lunch and take it to the Champs du Mar for a “picnic with a view”.

The Champs du Mar is the largest green space in Paris, with lovely views of the Eiffel Tower. 

So we headed out to the local boulangerie (bakery) for a baguette and mini quiche. Next stop was the marché aux fruits (fruit market), then charcuterie at the Italian bouchère (butcher) down the street and, of course, a stop at the chocolatier (the oldest chocolatier in Paris, (right outside our apartment door!) for a tiny box of fine French chocolate.

The last stop was a small cave à vins (wine shop). Scott picked out a bottle of Rosé. The very French (and minimal English-speaking) proprietor shook her head vigorously and pointed to a different Rosé. She told us that this bottle was "WAY much better!"

Scott paid for the wine while I waited outside. When he came out, he said, "Now I know why she recommended THAT bottle of Rosé". I asked, "why?". He replied, "It was 4x as much as the other bottle"! C'est la vie! 🇫🇷

We packed up all the gourmet treasures into our backpacks and headed to the Champs du Mar. Truly it was a picnic that will bring smiles whenever we recall it for years to come!

Although the skies were clear and brilliant blue, today was not a “fairy tale “ day but rather a sobering, emotional one that evoked immense gratitude. 

We visited the WW2 Memorial Museum in Caen, France and then it was on to  the American cemetery overlooking Omaha beach. 9,388 soldiers, who gave their lives to ensure our freedom on D Day (and the months that followed)are buried beneath the emerald green, immaculately maintained lawn. 

White Italian marble crosses stand  in perfect rows as far as the eye can see.  The precisely aligned grave markers all face towards America, the brave soldiers homeland. 

A special variety of coral-hued roses are planted throughout the cemetery cultivated to bloom April through October in memorial.

It was a day that will not be soon forgotten! #cafesucrefarine #ontheroadagain #omahabeach #ilovefrance #cafesucreadventures #vikingrivercruise #vikingcruises @vikingcruises
